      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "505e23f4f3a9e4c9",
      "text": "[…] The idea underlying this consideration is simple. It is based on the assumption that the stratification of the European Middle Ages developed an orderly, flat [[Address]], the contours of which were shaped by the relatively clear image of strata in which one was 'resident' by birth, strata that (with the exception of careers in the ecclesiastical context) could not be abandoned without difficulty and that fixed quite precisely what and how someone was allowed to be and what and how, therefore, exactly not. The address was stratified and left little room for individual design and for self-reference lived out in a way that was difficult to understand."
